data.content:
Your assertions work but `Assert.IsTrue` gives poor failure messages (just "expected True, was False"). MSTest 3.x has specialized collection assertions with much better diagnostics:

```csharp
[TestMethod]
public void GetActiveUsers_ReturnsOnlyActiveUsers()
{
    var service = new UserService();
    var users = service.GetActiveUsers();

    Assert.IsNotEmpty(users);                          // was: Assert.IsTrue(users.Count > 0)
    Assert.HasCount(3, users);                         // was: Assert.IsTrue(users.Count() == 3)
    Assert.IsTrue(users.All(u => u.IsActive));         // no built-in "all match" assertion, this is fine
    Assert.Contains(users.Single(u => u.Role == "Admin"), users); // or:
    // var admin = Assert.ContainsSingle(users.Where(u => u.Role == "Admin"));
}
```

**Key replacements:**

| Instead of | Use | Better failure message |
|---|---|---|
| `Assert.IsTrue(list.Count > 0)` | `Assert.IsNotEmpty(list)` | "Expected non-empty collection" |
| `Assert.IsTrue(list.Count() == 3)` | `Assert.HasCount(3, list)` | "Expected count: 3, Actual: 5" |
| `Assert.IsTrue(x != null)` | `Assert.IsNotNull(x)` | "Expected non-null value" |
| `.Single()` + null check | `Assert.ContainsSingle(filtered)` | "Expected single element, found 0" |

The biggest win is **debuggability** — when a test fails, you immediately see *what* went wrong instead of just `Assert.IsTrue failed`.
